<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Lotus unifoliolatus </i>is a native, cool-season, annual herb to 75 cm. Herbage is usually soft-hairy with three pinnately compound leaflets. Flowers are pinkish to yellowish white, occurring separately on > 1 cm long stalks. Var. <i>unifoliolatus </i>is common across various habitats in western North America with var. <i>helleri </i>in the Southeast. The name <i>L. purshianus </i>was previously used for this taxon, while the Jepson eFlora uses the name <i>Acmispon americanus</i> var. <i>americanus</i> (Jepson Flora Project 2017).<br/>
<br/>
Stands having > 25% cover or >50% relative cover of <i>L. unifoliolatus </i>are included in this alliance. Stands appear to be early seral, being found on disturbed sites that have well-developed soils, including flooded soils and grazed, mesic flats. This alliance was cited as <i>Lotus purshianus</i> Provisional Herbaceous Alliance in the 2009 book, <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>. It is unclear the difference between this and the <i>Bidens cernua - Euthamia occidentalis - Ludwigia palustris</i> alliance; more sampling and analysis are needed in moist to wet habitats to fully elucidate relationships. </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The range of <i>Lotus unifoliolatus</i> includes both cismontane and transmontane California. Multiple stands at Cosumnes River Preserve (Buck 2007) and generally in the Great Valley (262A; Buck-Diaz et al. 2012) have <i>L. unifoliolatus</i> as the dominant on floodplains. Two stands on the Modoc Plateau (M261G) have <i>Lotus micranthus</i> or <i>L. unifoliolatus</i> as the dominant in alluvial flats and terraces (S. Smith 1998b), and another stand was surveyed in 2016 (VegCAMP, in  process). Unclassified stands in the central to northern portion of the Sierra Nevada Foothills (M261Fa-Fb) show <i>L. unifoliolatus</i> sharing dominance with <i>H. brachyantherum</i> (Klein et al. 2007). Observations of dense patches of <i>L. unifoliolatus</i> have been seen in other locations (M262Bm, M261Ed, 261Aa-Ac) (Calflora 2017). Currently, a <i>Lotus unifoliolatus</i> association [1] is recognized. It may be that the alliance has a broad distribution, but further surveys are needed. </div>
</div>

	

    
